window.SEARCH_INDEX = [
  {f:"exam-hints.html",t:"Professor's Test Hints",secs:[
    {s:"Professor's Test Hints",a:"",k:["Exam Prep"]},
    {s:"Week 1 Content",a:"week-1-content",k:["Week 1 Content","Anatomy & Early Development","Umbilical cord: 2 arteries (carry waste away), 1 vein (carries oxygenated blood to the baby) — it's \"backwards.\" On an exam, you want more A's.","Quickening (fetal movement felt by mom) by about 20 weeks .","Genetics","You will have to build and interpret a Punnett square ; the question will tell you if the disorder is dominant or recessive.","Know how traits are expressed: dominant needs 1 abnormal allele; recessive needs 2 .","Signs, Dating & Assessment","Naegele's Rule (you will calculate it): first day of LMP − 3 months + 7 days.","GTPAL — Gravida counts pregnancies, not babies (twins = one pregnancy), and includes the current one.","Fundal height should be within about 2 cm of gestational age in weeks.","Signs of pregnancy: presumptive (subjective) vs. probable (objective, e.g. a positive pregnancy test) vs. positive (only explained by pregnancy, e.g. the HCP palpates fetal movement).","Infections, Disorders & IPV","For each breast/gyn disorder and STI: know etiology, symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, and complications . (See the disorders quick-reference table .)","Genital herpes (HSV-2): start acyclovir at 36 weeks ; an active lesion at delivery = C-section .","Intimate partner violence: know what to do if it's disclosed — screen privately, do not mention it in front of others, provide resources / a safety plan."]},
    {s:"Week 2 Content",a:"week-2-content",k:["Week 2 Content","Hypertensive Disorders","★ Magnesium sulfate in preeclampsia is given to PREVENT SEIZURES — not to lower blood pressure. (\"I want 0% of you to get it wrong.\")","Mag therapeutic level: 4 to 7.","Mag toxicity: absent reflexes, decreased respiratory rate, decreased level of consciousness / slurred speech. Antidote: IV calcium gluconate. (Expected side effects = flushing, warmth, drowsiness.)","Acute severe HTN meds — know drug, route, and contraindication (not doses): IV labetalol (avoid in asthma — \"labetalol, lungs\"); IV hydralazine (avoid in tachycardia); oral nifedipine (avoid in tachycardia).","Low-dose aspirin 81 mg for anyone at risk for preeclampsia (started 12 to 28 weeks).","Diagnosis of hypertension = TWO readings of 140/90 or higher, at least 4 hours apart .","Minimum urine output at least 30 mL/hr — be able to calculate it.","Diabetes in Pregnancy","★ Gestational diabetes glucose goals: fasting under 95 , one hour under 140 , two hours under 120 .","3-hour glucose tolerance test: 2 of 4 values elevated = gestational diabetes (don't memorize the exact cutoffs).","Fetal Testing & Screening","★ NST reactive criteria: 32 weeks or more = 2 accelerations of at least 15 bpm above baseline lasting 15 sec within 20 min; under 32 weeks = 10 bpm for 10 sec.","★ CST is \"backwards\": Negative = reassuring (no late decelerations); Positive = bad (late decels with more than half of contractions).","Biophysical profile (BPP) components — BATMAN: Breathing, Amniotic fluid, Tone, Movement, plus the Non-Stress Test.","BPP scoring: each component is 0 or 2 (never a 1); if the score is not 8/8, do a non-stress test.","L/S ratio of 2:1 or higher = mature fetal lungs.","Quad screen / MSAFP: maternal blood at about 15 to 22 weeks; it is a SCREEN, not diagnostic .","AFP: HIGH = open neural tube defects (spina bifida, anencephaly), also multiples/diabetes; LOW = Down syndrome or trisomy 18.","Maternal Nutrition","★ Folic acid: memorize at least 400 mcg/day (during pregnancy or when trying to conceive).","Cardiac Disorders","Focus on signs of cardiac decompensation and reducing cardiac workload — not the individual disorders."]},
    {s:"Week 3 Content",a:"week-3-content",k:["Week 3 Content","These now include the Week 3 live class (Dr. Clark) plus the recorded Intrapartum lectures. A ★ marks the items she flagged as fair game for a quiz or exam. (The very beginning of the live class wasn't captured, so a few opening points m…","Labor & Birth (Intrapartum I)","★ Fetal position from a picture: she said she \"could show you on a quiz or an exam\" a picture and ask for the three-letter position notation . Read it in order: side ( R/L of the mother) · landmark ( O cciput, M entum, S acrum, A cromion…","Station: the ischial spines are zero station and are the narrowest part of the pelvis; above = negative (−1 to −5), below = positive (+1 to +5). +4 = birth is imminent (the head is visible).","Dilation 0–10 cm; effacement 0–100%. Never push before 10 cm (fully dilated) — pushing on an incomplete cervix can tear it or make it swell.","True labor = progressive cervical change. The stage/phase is judged by dilation (latent 0–3, active 4–7, transition 8–10); engagement = 0 station .","Contraction frequency = start of one contraction to the start of the next (in minutes).","Third stage ≤ 30 min (longer = hemorrhage / retained placenta risk); give oxytocin after the placenta delivers , then fundal massage .","4th stage: a soft/boggy fundus is uterine atony — the big postpartum-hemorrhage red flag.","Fetal Monitoring (Intrapartum II)","VEAL CHOP: V ariables = C ord compression · E arly = H ead compression · A ccelerations = O kay · L ate = P lacental insufficiency. She teaches interventions with UNCOIL: change position (left side), Oxygen / turn Oxytocin off, IV fluid …","★ Accelerations — she said she will always give you the gestational age: ≥ 32 weeks = 15 bpm above baseline for 15 sec; < 32 weeks = 10 bpm for 10 sec.","Variability is the BEST indicator of fetal oxygenation (moderate 6–25 is what you want; absent is ominous / category III).","Decelerations by cause: early = head compression (benign — do a vaginal exam, the baby's getting low); late = uteroplacental insufficiency (a perfusion problem — always fix); variable = cord compression (reposition first; think nuchal co…","Sinusoidal pattern = the baby may be acidotic → deliver , notify the provider immediately.","Fetal tachycardia (>160 for ≥10 min): check the maternal temperature FIRST (rule out infection/fever).","Montevideo units (IUPC): peak minus resting baseline, summed over 10 min — want >200 (≤300) for adequate labor; resting tone <25 ; tachysystole = ≥6 contractions in 10 min .","Best place to hear the FHR = over the fetal shoulders/back (use Leopold's to find it). For ROA, listen in the RLQ .","GBS: penicillin during labor (drug of choice); clindamycin 900 mg IV q4h if penicillin-allergic. Terbutaline for tachysystole — hold if maternal HR ≥120 .","Triage tip: if she's thrashing and the toco isn't registering contractions, palpate the fundus first (rule out abruption/rupture) before readjusting the monitor or medicating."]},
    {s:"Not Tested",a:"not-tested",k:["Not Tested","She said you do NOT need to memorize these","Which genetic disorders are dominant vs. recessive (the question tells you).","The four quad-screen substances / what MSAFP screens for.","The exact 3-hour glucose tolerance test cutoffs.","Exact doses of the severe-hypertension drugs.","The exact amount each nutrient need increases (except folic acid, 400 mcg).","The specific cardiac disorders.","Detailed severe-preeclampsia lab thresholds."]}
  ]},
  {f:"sprint-review-1.html",t:"Week 2 Lecture Review",secs:[
    {s:"Week 2 Lecture Review",a:"",k:["Exam Prep"]},
    {s:"Disorders Quick Reference",a:"disorders-quick-reference",k:["Disorders Quick Reference","For each of these, know the etiology, symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, and potential complications.","Fibrocystic breast changes — Likely estrogen/progesterone imbalance; most common benign breast disorder — Mobile, tender lumps/cysts; worse before menses — Mammogram, fine-needle aspiration — Limit caffeine & sodium; oral contraceptives …","Endometriosis — Unknown; theories = retrograde menstrual flow, inflammation, immune defect — Pelvic pain around menses; ages 20–45; often found during infertility workup — Laparoscopy — Surgical removal of tissue; OCPs (not if trying to …","Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS) — Unknown; enlarged ovaries with numerous small cysts — Irregular/absent periods, elevated testosterone/androgens, obesity, insulin resistance, acne, alopecia, hirsutism, deeper voice — History & physic…","Toxic Shock Syndrome — Staph aureus toxin; linked to super-absorbent tampons — Fever, sunburn-like rash on trunk, vomiting, hypotension, inflamed mucous membranes — Elevated BUN, liver enzymes (AST/ALT), bilirubin; low platelets — Hospit…","Bacterial Vaginosis — Decreased normal vaginal flora (frequent sex, douching) — Thin, watery, gray discharge; fishy odor — Slide prep; vaginal pH greater than 4.5 — Metronidazole (Flagyl), clindamycin cream — Increases risk of acquiring …","Vaginal Candidiasis — Antibiotics, OCPs, immunosuppression, diabetes — Thick, curd-like white discharge; severe itching, rash — Spores on microscopy — Fluconazole (Diflucan) or nystatin; avoid Diflucan in pregnancy (use topical agents) —…","Trichomoniasis — Trichomonas vaginalis (most common non-viral STI) — Yellow-green discharge, inflammation, itching, dysuria — Visualization on wet mount — Metronidazole; non-treatment trending in pregnancy — Preterm labor risk","Chlamydia — Bacterial STI; often asymptomatic — Thin purulent discharge, dysuria, lower abdominal pain — Culture of vaginal secretions — Azithromycin — Untreated: neonatal conjunctivitis, blindness, pneumonia","Gonorrhea — Bacterial STI — Purulent greenish-yellow discharge, dysuria, vulvar swelling — Culture — Ceftriaxone (Rocephin) + azithromycin — Untreated: neonatal blindness/eye problems; can cause PID","Herpes Simplex (HSV-1/HSV-2) — Herpes simplex virus — Single or clustered vesicles; itching/tingling before outbreak — Lesion culture — Acyclovir (suppresses, no cure); start at 36 wks gestation — Active lesion at delivery: C-section req…","Human Papillomavirus (HPV) — Viral STI (vaginal, oral, or anal transmission) — Genital warts, or none — Biopsy; abnormal Pap smear — Cryotherapy, shave/acid removal; Gardasil vaccine (prevention) — Leading cause of cervical cancer; long …","Syphilis — T. pallidum, contact with open wound; can be congenital — Chancre to wart-like plaque; fever, weight loss, malaise — VDRL or RPR (RPR preferred) — Penicillin — Congenital transmission: IUGR, preterm birth, stillbirth","Pelvic Inflammatory Disease — Risk factors: multiple partners, IUD use, untreated gonorrhea/chlamydia — Bilateral sharp cramping pain, fever, chills, purulent discharge; can be asymptomatic — Vaginal culture, CBC, VDRL/RPR (rule out syph…","Urinary Tract Infections — Cystitis (lower): E. coli/staph. Pyelonephritis (upper): ascending, untreated lower UTI — Cystitis: low-grade fever, hematuria, dysuria. Pyelonephritis: high fever, chills, unilateral flank pain — Urine culture…"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week1-antepartum.html",t:"Antepartum Care",secs:[
    {s:"Antepartum Care",a:"",k:["Week 1 · Topic 3","Intimate partner violence is the most common form of violence against women, and pregnancy increases its incidence. Screen privately, without the partner present, and provide resources discreetly (e.g., pamphlets in patient-only restrooms)."]},
    {s:"Physiologic Changes of Pregnancy, by Body System",a:"physiologic-changes-of-pregnancy-by-body-system",k:["Physiologic Changes of Pregnancy, by Body System","Reproductive — Uterus grows from ~2 oz to ~2.5 lb (holds up to 5 L); Braxton Hicks contractions; Goodell's sign (cervix softens), Chadwick's sign (bluish cervix), Hegar's sign (uterus softens); mucus plug forms; colostrum may leak — Hype…","Respiratory — Increased O2 consumption; ribcage flares (↑ subcostal angle/AP diameter); breathing shifts abdominal→thoracic; nasal stuffiness, nosebleeds — Enlarging uterus elevates the diaphragm; vascular congestion of nasal mucosa","Cardiovascular — Blood volume ↑ 40–50%; physiologic (pseudo) anemia; ↓ vascular resistance; ↑ cardiac output; hypercoagulable state; risk of supine hypotensive syndrome — Plasma volume rises faster than RBC count; increased clotting fact…","Gastrointestinal — Nausea/vomiting; gum softening/bleeding; ↑ saliva; constipation; hemorrhoids; heartburn; gallstones — ↑ hCG; ↓ gastric emptying and peristalsis (progesterone); sphincter relaxation; uterine pressure on pelvic vessels","Renal — Dilation of kidneys/ureters; ↑ GFR and renal plasma flow; urinary frequency — Increased blood flow and uterine pressure on the bladder","Integumentary — Hyperpigmentation (areola, nipples, perianal); striae; chloasma (\"mask of pregnancy\"); spider nevi; linea nigra; ↓ body hair growth; ↑ sweat/sebaceous activity — Hormone-driven; chloasma worsened by sun exposure, fades po…","Musculoskeletal — Pelvic joints relax (\"waddle\" gait); lordosis and shifted center of gravity; diastasis recti — Relaxin/pregnancy hormones; enlarging uterus","Eye / Cognitive / Metabolic — ↓ intraocular pressure; corneal thickening; \"pregnancy brain\" (↓ attention/concentration/memory); ↑ stored water, fat, protein — Fluid retention; fat storage supports fetal brain development","Endocrine — Thyroid enlarges; ↑ parathyroid hormone; prolactin & oxytocin support lactation; oxytocin also drives contractions; ↑ aldosterone (↑ Na⁺ excretion); ↑ vasopressin (↑ BP) — Anterior/posterior pituitary and thyroid adaptation t…"]},
    {s:"Signs of Pregnancy",a:"signs-of-pregnancy",k:["Signs of Pregnancy","Amenorrhea Nausea/vomiting Excessive fatigue Urinary frequency Breast tenderness/enlargement Quickening — Goodell's, Chadwick's, Hegar's signs Abdominal enlargement Braxton Hicks contractions Abdominal striae Uterine souffle Skin pigment…","Presumptive signs can all be explained by things other than pregnancy (e.g., amenorrhea in an athlete). Positive signs can only be explained by pregnancy."]},
    {s:"Recommended Weight Gain",a:"recommended-weight-gain",k:["Recommended Weight Gain","Underweight — 28–40 lb","Normal weight — 25–35 lb","Overweight — 15–25 lb","Obese — 11–20 lb","Typical pattern: ~1 lb/week during the last two trimesters, after the first trimester."]},
    {s:"Psychological & Social Adaptation",a:"psychological-social-adaptation",k:["Psychological & Social Adaptation","Maternal Emotional Responses","Ambivalence — contradictory emotions (happy but fearful)","Acceptance — how she feels about being pregnant","Introversion — focus turns inward, onto how pregnancy affects her","Mood swings","Fear — of the unknown, of a repeat difficult pregnancy, of labor pain","Body image changes — can be harder if there's a prior eating disorder or poor body image","Rubin's Tasks of Pregnancy","Ensure safe passage through pregnancy, labor, birth","Seek acceptance of the child by others","Seek commitment/acceptance of self as mother (\"binding in\")","Learn to give of oneself on behalf of the child","Partner response: may feel confused by mood changes, left out, or resentful of the attention shift — include partners in teaching/visits. Couvade syndrome: partner experiences pregnancy-like symptoms (fatigue, sleep trouble, weight gain)…"]},
    {s:"Antepartal History & GTPAL",a:"antepartal-history-gtpal",k:["Antepartal History & GTPAL","A thorough prenatal history covers: current/past pregnancies, gynecologic and medical history (incl. substance use), family medical history, religious/spiritual/cultural/occupational history, partner history and health, and psychosocial …","G — Gravida — Total pregnancies, including the current one","T — Term — Deliveries at 37 weeks or later","P — Preterm — Deliveries 20w0d–36w6d","A — Abortions — Losses before 20 weeks (spontaneous, induced, ectopic, molar)","L — Living — Number of living children"]},
    {s:"Dating the Pregnancy",a:"dating-the-pregnancy",k:["Dating the Pregnancy","Naegele's Rule — First day of LMP − 3 months + 7 days. Example: LMP Sept 1 → EDB = June 8.","EDB wheel — Dial tool — point to the LMP date and read the corresponding due date/current gestational age","McDonald's method (fundal height) — Symphysis pubis → fundus, in cm, correlates with weeks gestation between 22–34 weeks (±2 cm). At ~20 weeks the fundus is roughly at the umbilicus."]},
    {s:"Prenatal Screening Tests",a:"prenatal-screening-tests",k:["Prenatal Screening Tests","Pap smear — Initial visit — Cervical cancer screening","CBC — Initial visit — Checks hemoglobin/anemia","Rubella titer — Initial visit — Immunity to rubella (measles)","Blood type & Rh factor — Initial visit — Determines need for Rh antibody protection (Rhogam)","Hepatitis B & C screen — Initial visit — Infection screening","STI panel — Initial visit — Syphilis, gonorrhea, chlamydia","Sickle cell screen — Initial visit — Offered for patients of African or Latino descent","Cystic fibrosis screen — Initial visit (optional) — Carrier screening","HIV — Initial visit — Universal screening","Drug screen — Initial visit — Urine or blood","Urine dipstick — Each visit — Protein, glucose","Urine culture — ~12–16 weeks — UTI screening — untreated UTI can lead to preterm labor","Quad screen — ~15–20 weeks — Estriol, hCG, AFP, inhibin A — genetic risk screening","Glucose screen — ~24–28 weeks — Gestational diabetes screening","Group B Strep (GBS) — ~35–37 weeks — Determines need for intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis","NIPT (cell-free DNA) — As indicated — Chromosomal risk screening","Quad screen AFP: High AFP → neural tube defects (spina bifida, anencephaly), multiples, maternal diabetes | Low AFP → increased risk of Down syndrome (trisomy 21) or Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18)"]},
    {s:"Danger Signs of Pregnancy — call the provider",a:"danger-signs-of-pregnancy-call-the-provider",k:["Danger Signs of Pregnancy — call the provider","Gush of fluid from vagina — Possible ruptured membranes","Vaginal bleeding — Placental complications","Abdominal pain — Multiple possible causes, needs evaluation","Fever unrelieved by acetaminophen — Infection/illness","Dizziness, blurred vision, visual spots — Neurologic warning signs of hypertension — check BP","Persistent vomiting — Risk of dehydration/electrolyte imbalance","Generalized or facial edema, or one-sided swelling — Possible preeclampsia","Seizure or muscular irritability — Neurologic emergency","Epigastric pain / pain under right breast — Liver tenderness — associated with hypertensive disorders","Decreased urine output / painful urination — Renal or infectious concern","Decreased fetal movement — Fetal wellbeing concern"]},
    {s:"Prenatal Visit Schedule",a:"prenatal-visit-schedule",k:["Prenatal Visit Schedule","Up to 28 weeks — Every 4 weeks","28–36 weeks — Every 2 weeks","36 weeks–birth — Every week","Averages out to roughly 10 prenatal visits for an uncomplicated pregnancy; more complex pregnancies are seen more frequently."]}
  ]},
  {f:"week1-disorders.html",t:"Disorders & Genetics",secs:[
    {s:"Disorders & Genetics",a:"",k:["Week 1 · Topic 2"]},
    {s:"Breast & Gynecologic Disorders",a:"breast-gynecologic-disorders",k:["Breast & Gynecologic Disorders","Fibrocystic breast changes — Most common benign breast disorder; likely estrogen/progesterone imbalance — Mobile, tender lumps/cysts; worse before menses. (Fixed mass + skin retraction is a red flag for cancer, not this.) — Mammogram, fi…","Endometriosis — Unknown — theories: retrograde menstrual flow, inflammation, immune defect — Pelvic pain around menses; common in ages 20–45; often found during infertility workup — Laparoscopy — Surgical removal of endometrial tissue; o…","PCOS — Unknown; enlarged ovaries with numerous small cysts — Irregular/absent periods, elevated testosterone/androgens, obesity, insulin resistance, infertility, acne, alopecia, hirsutism, deeper voice — History & physical, labs, transva…"]},
    {s:"Vaginal Infections",a:"vaginal-infections",k:["Vaginal Infections","Bacterial Vaginosis — Decreased normal vaginal flora (frequent sex, douching) — Thin, watery, whitish-gray discharge with fishy odor — Slide prep; vaginal pH > 4.5 — Metronidazole (Flagyl), clindamycin vaginal cream","Candidiasis (yeast) — Antibiotics, oral contraceptives, immunosuppression, diabetes — Thick, curd-like white discharge; severe itching, perineal/vulvar rash — Spores on microscopy — Fluconazole (Diflucan) or nystatin","Trichomoniasis — Trichomonas vaginalis (most common non-viral STI) — Yellow-green discharge, inflammation, itching, dysuria — Visualization of the organism on wet mount — Metronidazole. In pregnancy, evidence is shifting toward non-treat…","Toxic Shock Syndrome (TSS) Medical emergency — Staph aureus toxin; strongly linked to super-absorbent tampons or not changing them often enough — Fever, sunburn-like rash on the trunk, vomiting, hypotension, inflamed mucous membranes — ↑…"]},
    {s:"Sexually Transmitted Infections",a:"sexually-transmitted-infections",k:["Sexually Transmitted Infections","Chlamydia — Thin purulent discharge, dysuria, lower abdominal pain — often asymptomatic — Culture of vaginal secretions — Azithromycin — Untreated → neonatal conjunctivitis, blindness, pneumonia","Gonorrhea — Purulent greenish-yellow discharge, dysuria, vulvar swelling — Culture — Rocephin (ceftriaxone) + azithromycin — Untreated → neonatal blindness, eye problems","Herpes (HSV-1 cold sores / HSV-2 genital) — Single or clustered vesicles, itching/tingling before outbreak — Lesion culture — Acyclovir keeps virus dormant (no cure). Triggers: stress, menstruation, pregnancy, sex, tight clothing, heat —…","Syphilis — Chancre → wart-like plaque; fever, weight loss, malaise — VDRL or RPR (RPR preferred) — Penicillin — Can be acquired congenitally → IUGR, preterm birth, stillbirth","HPV — Genital warts (or none); leading cause of cervical cancer — Biopsy; abnormal Pap smear — Cryotherapy, shave removal, acid removal; Gardasil vaccine for prevention — Incubation can be years — a normal past Pap doesn't rule out later…","Pelvic Inflammatory Disease — Bilateral sharp cramping pain, fever, chills, purulent discharge — Vaginal culture, CBC, VDRL/RPR (to rule out syphilis) — Multi-antibiotic combination — Risk factors: multiple partners, IUD use, untreated g…"]},
    {s:"Urinary Tract Infections",a:"urinary-tract-infections",k:["Urinary Tract Infections","Cause — Usually E. coli or staph — Ascending, untreated/unresolved lower UTI","Signs/Symptoms — Low-grade fever, hematuria, dysuria — High fever, chills, flank pain (usually unilateral)","Treatment — Antibiotics per culture — IV fluids, IV antibiotics, possible pain medication"]},
    {s:"Infertility",a:"infertility",k:["Infertility","Essential Female Fertility Factors","Favorable cervical mucus","Patent, normally motile fallopian tubes","Ovaries producing/releasing normal eggs","No obstruction between ovary and uterus","Favorable endometrium","Adequate reproductive hormones","Essential Male Fertility Factors","Normal sperm quality, quantity, motility","Unobstructed genital tract","Normal genital tract secretions","Sperm able to reach the cervix","Primary infertility: no conception after 12 months of unprotected sex. Secondary infertility: unable to conceive/sustain pregnancy after a prior successful pregnancy. Tips to improve fertility: avoid douching/artificial lubricants, retai…","Infertility Workup","Basal body temperature (BBT) — Body temperature rises/spikes when progesterone increases after ovulation; charting it helps pinpoint when ovulation occurs","Cervical mucus monitoring — Near ovulation the discharge becomes thinner, more abundant, and more elastic — a sign of potential ovulation","Hormone assessment — Checks FSH and LH levels; the day of the LH surge is typically the most fertile day","Endometrial biopsy — Checks the effect of progesterone on the endometrium after ovulation","Transvaginal ultrasound — Evaluates anatomy (two ovaries, patent tubes), blood flow, and egg maturity","Male workup — Evaluates for ductal obstruction and abnormal sperm or sperm-production problems","Infertility Treatment Options","Clomiphene citrate (Clomid) — Stimulates follicle growth and egg release","Progesterone supplementation — For inadequate progesterone levels","Gonadotropins (FSH/LH) — For inadequate FSH/LH levels","Bromocriptine (Parlodel) — Inhibits prolactin → increases FSH/LH → induces ovulation","Therapeutic insemination — Donor/partner sperm placed at cervix/uterus — helpful for low sperm count/motility","In Vitro Fertilization (IVF) — Egg fertilized in lab, embryo placed in uterus — used for tubal blockage, mucus/cervical factors, male factor, same-sex couples with donor sperm","Gamete Intrafallopian Transfer (GIFT) — Egg + sperm placed together in the fallopian tube; fertilization occurs naturally in the body","Zygote Intrafallopian Transfer (ZIFT) — Egg fertilized in lab, then placed back in the fallopian tube (uncommon)","Adoption — Domestic or international — use reputable agencies; can be a lengthy, costly process","Psychosocial effects of infertility: strain on the relationship, guilt/frustration, anger/shame, loss of control, feelings of incompetence, social stigma, strained relationship with the provider."]},
    {s:"Genetics",a:"genetics",k:["Genetics","Karyotype: pictorial view of an individual's chromosomes. Phenotype: the observable expression of a trait (hair/eye color, etc.). Humans have 22 pairs of autosomes + 1 pair of sex chromosomes.","Chromosomal Disorders","Down Syndrome — Trisomy 21 (3 copies of chromosome 21) — Identified via karyotype","Translocation — Chromosomal material reordered, not missing (e.g., 14/21) — Often clinically normal; can affect fertility/offspring genetics — usually discovered during a fertility workup or prenatal testing","Turner Syndrome — Monosomy X (single, inactive X chromosome) — female — Low-set ears, heart problems, abnormal jaw, wide neck; fertility issues","Klinefelter Syndrome — XXY — male — Small testes, low/no sperm, decreased muscle mass, increased breast tissue; fertility issues","Autosomal Dominant vs. Recessive Inheritance","Autosomal Dominant","Affected individual has an affected parent","50% chance of passing the defect to each child","Only one abnormal allele needed","Examples: Huntington's disease, dwarfism, polydactyly","Aa affected — aa unaffected","Affected (Aa) × Unaffected (aa) → 50% affected","Autosomal Recessive","Affected individual has two clinically normal, carrier parents","Carrier × carrier → 25% affected, 50% carrier, 25% unaffected","Requires two abnormal alleles (homozygous recessive)","Example: Cystic fibrosis","BB unaffected — Bb carrier","Bb carrier — bb affected","Carrier (Bb) × Carrier (Bb) → 25% / 50% / 25%","Prenatal Genetic Testing","Ultrasound — Visualizes the fetus directly for structural abnormalities","Amniocentesis — Genetic material from amniotic fluid — chromosomal disorders/syndromes; used for advanced maternal age, prior affected child, abnormal screen","Chorionic Villus Sampling (CVS) — Genetic/chromosomal material from chorionic villi","Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) — Maternal blood test — high = neural tube defects (spina bifida); low = increased Down syndrome risk","NIPT (cell-free DNA) — Measures circulating fetal cell-free DNA in maternal blood — for older mothers, abnormal ultrasound, prior affected child"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week1-reproductive.html",t:"Anatomy & Physiology",secs:[
    {s:"Anatomy & Physiology",a:"",k:["Week 1 · Topic 1"]},
    {s:"External Genitalia (Vulva)",a:"external-genitalia-vulva",k:["External Genitalia (Vulva)","Mons pubis — Protects the pelvic bones","Labia majora — Protect the underlying tissues","Labia minora — Lubricate vulvar skin; secrete a bactericidal fluid","Clitoris — Female erectile tissue","Urethral meatus — Urine outlet — when catheterizing a pregnant patient, aim high and lift the labia to visualize it (tissue is more swollen/congested)","Skene's glands — Paraurethral glands that lubricate the vaginal opening","Hymen — Thin tissue around the vaginal opening — can be stretched/torn by tampons, exercise, etc., not only intercourse","Perineal body — Stretches during delivery; common site of episiotomy/laceration"]},
    {s:"Internal Genitalia",a:"internal-genitalia",k:["Internal Genitalia","Vagina — Muscular tube connecting external genitals to uterus — the birth canal","Fundus — Rounded upper portion of the uterus; massaged postpartum to control bleeding","Cervix (internal/external os) — Internal os is closest to the uterus, external os closest to the vagina — both thin during effacement","Endometrium — Inner uterine lining — site of implantation","Myometrium — Muscle layer of the uterus","Perimetrium — Outer layer of the uterus","Fornices (ant./post.) — Space around the cervix that allows semen to pool, aiding sperm transport","Internal genitalia — sagittal view","Uterus — layers and internal/external os","Uterine Ligaments","Broad ligament — Sheath over the pelvic cavity; provides stability, keeps uterus centrally placed","Round ligament — Pulls the uterus down and forward, helping the presenting part enter the cervix — source of round ligament pain in pregnancy","Cardinal ligament — Chief uterine support — helps prevent uterine prolapse","Fallopian Tubes & Ovaries","Isthmus — Connects the fallopian tube to the uterus — site of tubal ligation","Ampulla — Usual site of fertilization","Fimbriae — Finger-like projections that sweep the released egg into the tube","Ovaries — Hold all eggs a woman will ever have (present at birth); primary source of estrogen/progesterone until the placenta takes over progesterone production around week 7; the ovaries resume control after delivery","Fallopian tube & ovary — isthmus, ampulla, fimbriae","Bony Pelvis","False pelvis — Supports the weight of the enlarging uterus; directs fetus toward the true pelvis","True pelvis — Must be adequate in size for vaginal delivery — inadequate size is cephalopelvic disproportion (CPD)","Ischial spines — Narrowest diameter of the pelvis = 0 station (fetal engagement)","Pelvic inlet / outlet — Inlet diameter determines engagement; outlet determines whether the baby can pass under the pubic arch (outlet/shoulder dystocia if not)","False vs. true pelvis","Pelvic inlet & ischial spines"]},
    {s:"Female Hormones",a:"female-hormones",k:["Female Hormones","Estrogen — Female secondary sex characteristics: breast development, hip widening, uterine growth, increased body hair, sexual desire","Progesterone — Stabilizes uterus for implantation, thickens cervical mucus, supports lactation and breast glandular tissue","Prostaglandins — Fatty acids that relax/constrict smooth muscle — relevant to labor induction and increasing contractions","FSH — Follicle-stimulating hormone — matures the egg follicle","LH — Luteinizing hormone — triggers ovulation; decreases estrogen while allowing progesterone secretion to continue","Menstrual / Ovarian Cycle (~28-day average)","Two processes run in parallel — the ovarian cycle (egg maturation) and the uterine cycle (endometrial preparation).","Follicular — Immature egg matures under FSH; ends in ovulation (day 13–15, most fertile window)","Luteal — Egg travels to the ampulla; if fertilized, implants ~3–4 days later and begins secreting hCG. Egg is only fertile 12–24 hrs.","Menstrual — Endometrial shedding/bleeding, typically 2–8 days","Proliferative — Endometrium thickens under rising estrogen; cervical mucus becomes clear/elastic, favorable for sperm","Secretory — Follows ovulation — progesterone causes marked vascular swelling to build a nourishing implantation bed","Ischemic — If no implantation, estrogen/progesterone drop, corpus luteum degenerates → menstrual phase begins","The female cycle — uterine & ovarian phases over 28 days"]},
    {s:"Male Reproductive System",a:"male-reproductive-system",k:["Male Reproductive System","Penis — Contains the urethra; external organ","Scrotum — Houses the testes; keeps sperm temperature below core body temp","Testes — Site of sperm production; secrete testosterone","Epididymis — Sperm reservoir, sits behind each testis","Vas deferens & ejaculatory duct — Connect the epididymis to the prostate for sperm passage","Seminal vesicles — Secrete alkaline fluid that aids sperm motility and metabolism","Prostate gland — Encircles the urethra; secretes fluid that protects sperm from the acidic vaginal environment","Urethra — Shared pathway — sperm and urine are not released simultaneously if the ejaculatory duct is functioning normally","Male reproductive anatomy","Sperm head carries all genetic material; the tail provides motility. Sperm remain viable 48–72 hrs (most fertile ~24 hrs). Undescended testes at birth are not a fertility concern as long as they descend (spontaneously or surgically) befo…","Mitosis vs. Meiosis","Mitosis","Growth and tissue repair","Produces exact copies of original cells","Full chromosome number retained","Meiosis (gametogenesis)","Produces eggs and sperm","Cells contain only half the genetic material","Oogenesis : complete at birth (female)","Spermatogenesis : begins at puberty (male)","Fertilization: 23 (maternal) + 23 (paternal) alleles = 46 chromosomes. Sex chromosomes: XX = female, XY = male. Fertilization typically occurs in the ampulla; only one sperm is meant to enter the egg."]},
    {s:"Twins",a:"twins",k:["Twins","Fraternal (Dizygotic)","Two eggs, two sperm, two separate blastocysts. Share only uterine space — can be any sex combination. Two placentas, two chorions, two amnions.","Identical (Monozygotic)","One egg + one sperm → one blastocyst that later divides. Always same sex. How much they share depends on when the division occurs.","Confirming on Ultrasound","One boy + one girl = definitely fraternal. Two of the same sex = could be either fraternal or identical.","Identical Twin Subtypes — by timing of blastocyst division","Dichorionic-Diamniotic (Di-Di) — ~3 days — 2 — 2 — Lowest risk (separate or fused placentas)","Monochorionic-Diamniotic (Mono-Di) — ~5 days — 1 (shared) — 2 — Higher risk — shared chorion","Monochorionic-Monoamniotic (Mono-Mono) — 8–12 days — 1 (shared) — 1 (shared) — Highest risk — share the same amniotic sac; risk of cord entanglement","Fraternal (dizygotic) — 2 amnions, 2 chorions","Identical (monozygotic) — inner cell mass splits"]},
    {s:"Amniotic Fluid, Cord & Placenta",a:"amniotic-fluid-cord-placenta",k:["Amniotic Fluid, Cord & Placenta","Polyhydramnios — > 2,000 mL fluid — Multiple gestation, maternal diabetes (fetal polyuria from hyperglycemia), fetal GI/swallowing problems","Oligohydramnios — < 400 mL fluid, or AFI < 5 (normal AFI 5–25 cm) — Maternal perfusion issues (e.g., hypertension), fetal kidney problems, bladder obstruction","Umbilical cord: 2 arteries (carry waste away) + 1 vein (delivers oxygenated blood) surrounded by Wharton's jelly; no pain receptors, so cutting it doesn't hurt mom or baby. Placenta: provides immune protection, excretion, respiration, nu…"]},
    {s:"Fetal Development Timeline",a:"fetal-development-timeline",k:["Fetal Development Timeline","Heart begins to beat (often before the mother knows she's pregnant); arm/leg buds, vertebrae, lung buds present; eyes/ears forming","Body straightens, trachea develops, liver produces blood cells, blood begins circulating, digits developing","Face more developed, eyelids closed, tooth buds appear, genitals differentiated, urine produced, spontaneous movement begins (not yet felt by mom)","Halfway point. Subcutaneous brown fat, vernix, and lanugo form; nipples and nails present; most mothers begin feeling fetal movement (quickening); FHTs audible by fetoscope","Eyes structurally complete, alveoli begin forming, grasp/startle reflexes and fingerprints/footprints present — chance of survival if born now","Rapid brain development, eyelids open, testes begin descending, improved gas exchange","Increasing subcutaneous fat, lanugo disappearing, 4 weeks from term","Smooth/polished skin, vernix remains mainly in creases, head larger than chest"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week2-antepartum2.html",t:"Antepartum Care II",secs:[
    {s:"Antepartum Care II",a:"",k:["Week 2 · Topic 1"]},
    {s:"Common Pregnancy Discomforts",a:"common-pregnancy-discomforts",k:["Common Pregnancy Discomforts","A frequent test topic: know the discomfort, why it happens, and how to relieve it.","Nausea & vomiting — Increased hCG, especially early in pregnancy — Dry crackers or toast before rising; small frequent meals; avoid greasy/spicy foods; carbonated beverages; antiemetics if severe","Urinary frequency — Uterus pressing on the bladder — Void every 2 hours during the day","Fatigue — Hormonal; worse with other children or a busy schedule — Encourage good rest periods","Breast tenderness — Increased progesterone & estrogen; larger breasts — Wear a supportive bra","Leukorrhea (increased vaginal discharge) — Natural secretions that lubricate and prevent infection; milky white, thin, mild/no odor — Daily bathing, cotton underwear; normal — not a cause for alarm","Nasal stuffiness — Increased estrogen levels — Cool-air vaporizer; normal saline nasal spray","Heartburn — Uterus displaces the stomach; esophageal sphincter relaxes — Non-sodium antacids as recommended by provider","Ankle edema — Decreased venous return from lower extremities — Avoid prolonged sitting/standing; elevate feet and legs","Varicose veins — Decreased circulation to lower extremities; weight gain — Regular exercise; avoid prolonged sitting/standing","Flatulence / gas — Decreased GI motility; uterus pressing on large intestines — Avoid gas-producing foods; regular bowel habits","Hemorrhoids — Constipation, increased progesterone, iron supplements, decreased motility → hardened stool — Gentle self-reduction, topical ointments, warm soaks & sitz baths","Constipation — Iron supplements, decreased motility, increased progesterone — Increase fluids and roughage; daily exercise; regular bowel habits","Backache — Softening of cartilage/joints and lordosis of the back — Pelvic tilt exercises, good posture, avoid fatigue, good body mechanics","Leg cramps — Uterus pressure on nerves; poor circulation — Massage, warm soaks, stretching (dorsiflex the foot to stretch the calf)","Faintness — Changes in blood volume, postural hypotension, possible anemia — Sit down and lower head between knees; avoid standing in one place too long","Shortness of breath — Uterus pushes up on the diaphragm — Good posture when sitting; prop up in bed","Difficulty sleeping — Nocturia, active baby, enlarged uterus, leg cramps — Maximize comfort with pillows; avoid caffeine","Round ligament pain — Ligaments stretching to support the enlarging uterus — Warmth; pain medication if needed (one of the most common complaints)","Carpal tunnel syndrome — Compression of the median nerve in the wrist — Avoid repetitive hand movements; wrist splints; may resolve after delivery (occasionally needs surgery)","Shortness of breath vs. dyspnea: Normal SOB follows activity (e.g., climbing stairs) and resolves with a few minutes of rest. Dyspnea is difficulty breathing that occurs even at rest, when the patient wasn't doing anything — check a puls…"]},
    {s:"Self-Care During Pregnancy",a:"self-care-during-pregnancy",k:["Self-Care During Pregnancy","Fetal movement / kick counts","Movement felt ~16–22 weeks (most by 20 weeks; earlier if not the first baby)","Check the same time each day; lie on the side ~1 hour after eating","<2 movements in a 2-hour period (after eating, drinking, emptying the bladder) → contact provider","Breast care","Supportive bra; keep breasts clean","No soap on the nipples — it dries them out","Breast/nipple shield for flat or inverted nipples, worn the last 3–4 weeks to train the nipple to be more erect","Clothing & hygiene","Avoid high heels (center of gravity is off) and restrictive clothing","Daily bathing (culture-dependent); at least keep the perineal area clean","Avoid hyperthermia in the first trimester (no hot tubs / overly warm water) during early fetal development","Employment & travel","Can work until labor starts unless complications; watch environmental hazards (heavy lifting, chemicals) and adjust the job as needed","Travel is fine unless complications; airlines may restrict late gestation","Car trips: frequent breaks to stretch; seat belt with the lap belt under the abdomen; be evaluated after any accident","Exercise","\"Not the time to learn a new sport,\" but staying active is good","Eat an additional 300 kcal/day ; avoid overheating","Benefits: self-image, energy, sleep, tension relief, weight control, bowel function","Kegel exercises strengthen the pelvic floor and reduce urine leakage","Contraindications: ruptured membranes, elevated BP, cervical insufficiency, vaginal bleeding, preterm labor, abnormal placenta placement","Sexual activity","1st trimester: less desire (fatigue, nausea)","2nd trimester: fewer discomforts; libido may increase (perineal vascular congestion)","3rd trimester: may revert (fatigue, SOB, decreased mobility)","No restrictions unless the provider has advised against it","Dental care","Continue regular checkups; brush at least twice daily","Poor dentition can lead to chronic conditions and infections","Avoid routine dental x-rays until after delivery (unless an absolute indication)","Vaccines","Be up to date before pregnancy","MMR (rubella) is a live virus — give after delivery (postpartum), not during pregnancy","Encourage the flu vaccine and Tdap (pertussis/whooping cough) in the third trimester of every pregnancy to pass antibodies to the baby"]},
    {s:"Teratogenic Substances",a:"teratogenic-substances",k:["Teratogenic Substances","Teratogens adversely affect normal fetal growth and development. Greatest risk is the first trimester , when the organs are forming.","Medications — Check the pregnancy risk category. Example: Accutane (acne) causes many birth defects — birth control is required to receive it. Remember: no medication is 100% safe in pregnancy","Tobacco — Preventable/modifiable; causes vasoconstriction. Low birth weight, preterm birth, PROM, possible fetal demise/stillbirth, abnormal placental implantation. After birth: ↑ SIDS, middle-ear & respiratory infections, behavioral/lea…","Alcohol — Fetal alcohol syndrome: growth restriction, facial anomalies (smooth philtrum, short nose, small head, underdeveloped jaw), intellectual disability; ↑ miscarriage, stillbirth, low birth weight. No established safe level","Caffeine — Limit to ~200 mg/day (about one cup of coffee). No clear link to birth defects, but can cause newborn hypersensitivity/jitteriness","Marijuana — Still considered a teratogen; limited research, unreliable strength/composition, possible gateway drug","Cocaine — Maternal: stroke, MI, dysrhythmias, ruptured aorta, seizures, abruption, PROM. Metabolizes fast (screen may be negative within 24–48 hrs) → test a segment of umbilical cord after delivery to reveal exposure","Facial features of fetal alcohol syndrome"]},
    {s:"Special Populations",a:"special-populations",k:["Special Populations","Advanced maternal age (≥ 35)","Considered high risk; often well-educated and financially secure; delayed childbearing","↑ miscarriage, gestational diabetes, gestational hypertension, placenta previa, difficult labor, C-section, multiple births","Down syndrome risk jumps notably around age 35 → offer screening/diagnostic testing","Possible social isolation (only ones in their peer group expecting)","Adolescent pregnancy","US has the highest adolescent birth rate among industrialized nations (KY ranked #6)","Contributing factors: poverty, low educational achievement, lack of after-school activity, multiple partners, inconsistent contraception, STIs, sense of invulnerability, family dysfunction, low self-esteem, abuse history","↑ preterm birth, low birth weight, preeclampsia/eclampsia, iron-deficiency anemia, cephalopelvic disproportion","A pregnant teen is an emancipated minor and can make her own medical decisions"]},
    {s:"Tests of Fetal Well-Being",a:"tests-of-fetal-well-being",k:["Tests of Fetal Well-Being","Ultrasound — High-frequency sound waves reflect off tissues; non-invasive, painless, non-radiating. Identifies anomalies, neural tube problems, skeletal malformations; used for decades with no known harmful effects","Nuchal translucency (NT) — Ultrasound of the clear area on the back of the fetal neck; done 11–14 weeks. >3 mm is at risk; detects 70–80% of Down syndrome cases. A screen , not diagnostic","Transvaginal ultrasound — Sterile probe, empty bladder; closer to structures for clearer images. Great predictor of preterm birth — measures cervical length and detects cervical funneling","Doppler flow studies (umbilical artery velocimetry) — Non-invasive; measures blood flow in maternal/fetal circulation (2nd–3rd trimester). ↑ S/D ratio = decreased uteroplacental perfusion; >95th percentile for gestational age is abnormal","Non-stress test (NST) — Monitors FHR with movement/contractions. Reactive = ≥2 accelerations of 15 bpm above baseline for 15 sec within 20 min (if ≥32 wks); if <32 wks, 10 bpm for 10 sec. Non-reactive doesn't always mean non-reassuring (…","Vibroacoustic stimulation — Sound/vibration used to stimulate the fetus; look for FHR accelerations in response","Biophysical profile (BPP) — Ultrasound scores 4 components (fetal breathing, movement, tone, amniotic fluid index), each 0 or 2 — no partial credit — plus the NST as a 5th. Normal = 8/8, or 10/10 with a reactive NST","Contraction stress test (CST) — Evaluates placental oxygen/CO₂ exchange under the stress of contractions. Negative (desired) = no late decelerations in 10 min; positive = late decels with >half of contractions (poor placental perfusion);…","Amniotic fluid analysis (amniocentesis) — Genetic testing and fetal lung maturity (lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio & surfactant, which keep alveoli open)","Chorionic villus sampling (CVS) — Done very early; risks include ruptured membranes, bleeding, infection, possible limb reduction, birth defects. Cannot detect neural tube defects","Reactive NST — accelerations with fetal movement","Non-reactive NST — flat baseline, no qualifying accelerations","Late decelerations (positive CST) — FHR dips after each contraction","Each category is all-or-nothing (2 if normal, 0 if abnormal). Four ultrasound components = up to 8/8; add a reactive NST for up to 10/10. If you don't get 8/8, follow up with an NST."]}
  ]},
  {f:"week2-complications.html",t:"Antepartum Complications",secs:[
    {s:"Antepartum Complications",a:"",k:["Week 2 · Topic 3"]},
    {s:"Diabetes in Pregnancy",a:"diabetes-in-pregnancy",k:["Diabetes in Pregnancy","An endocrine disorder of carbohydrate metabolism from inadequate insulin production or use. Classic signs: polyuria, polydipsia, polyphagia, weight loss.","Type 1 — Lack of insulin production","Type 2 — Insufficient insulin production","Gestational — Insufficient insulin production due to pregnancy","Insulin needs across pregnancy: In the first trimester the need decreases (pregnancy hormones enhance insulin production/response). From late first trimester onward the need increases — pregnancy hormones act as insulin antagonists, and …","Risks of Diabetes in Pregnancy","Maternal risks","Polyhydramnios (increased fetal urine)","Preeclampsia / eclampsia","Ketoacidosis (DKA) — a major cause of stillbirth","Dystocia (difficult labor from a large baby)","Infections — UTIs and yeast (extra glucose feeds bacteria)","Retinopathy; perinatal mortality","Fetal / neonatal risks","Congenital anomalies (high glucose during organ formation)","Macrosomia (large baby) and, conversely, IUGR from poor placental perfusion","Respiratory distress syndrome (fetal insulin inhibits surfactant enzymes)","Polycythemia (extra RBCs)","Neonatal hypoglycemia after delivery","Hyperbilirubinemia (immature liver + polycythemia breakdown)","Glucose Screening & Diagnosis","1-hour GTT (screening) — Non-fasting; drink 50 g glucose, draw blood 1 hour later — >140 mg/dL = failed screen → proceed to the 3-hour test","3-hour GTT (diagnostic) — Fasting; draw fasting level, drink 100 g glucose, then draw at 1, 2, and 3 hours — Diagnosed if ≥2 values are elevated: fasting ≥95, 1-hr >180, 2-hr >155, 3-hr >140","Keeping glucose in range helps prevent fetal macrosomia. Screening is usually at 24–28 weeks for low-risk patients, earlier for high-risk (obesity, family history, prior GDM, hypertension, glucose in the urine).","Management: diet therapy & exercise, glucose monitoring, insulin; dietitian referral; frequent ultrasounds, daily kick counts, NSTs. Deliver ≥39 weeks unless a complication. Assess glucose often (even hourly) in labor. Insulin needs drop…"]},
    {s:"Anemias in Pregnancy",a:"anemias-in-pregnancy",k:["Anemias in Pregnancy","Iron-deficiency — Inadequate iron intake → low hemoglobin — Fatigue; tolerates blood loss poorly. In pregnancy, diagnosed below ~11 g/dL (plasma volume dilutes the count). Treat with supplemental iron","Sickle cell — Autosomal recessive — needs two copies of the recessive allele; RBCs sickle when oxygen is low — Prevent/treat crisis with IV fluids, oxygen, antibiotics, folic acid, and analgesics","Folic acid deficiency — Lack of folic acid → RBCs fail to divide, becoming enlarged and fewer — Raises fetal neural tube defect risk. All childbearing-age women should take 400 mcg folic acid daily before pregnancy; prenatal vitamins add…"]},
    {s:"Recognizing Substance Abuse",a:"recognizing-substance-abuse",k:["Recognizing Substance Abuse","Prevention is the ideal nursing goal, so assessment and early identification matter. (The specific teratogenic substances are covered under Antepartum Care II.)","Possible signs","Vague or unusual complaints","History of abuse, depression, STIs, or prior drug use","Poor nutritional status; track marks","Mood swings, hallucinations","Frequent accidents and falls","Cirrhosis or hepatitis","Nursing approach","Teach the effects of substances on the mother and baby","Establish a trusting, non-judgmental relationship"]},
    {s:"HIV / AIDS in Pregnancy",a:"hiv-aids-in-pregnancy",k:["HIV / AIDS in Pregnancy","Transmission & testing","Antibodies detectable ~6–12 weeks (up to 6 months) — a woman can be infectious before she knows","Spread by sexual contact, contaminated blood, and perinatally/congenitally (vertical transmission)","Screen all pregnancies; retest at-risk women in the third trimester","Reducing transmission","ZDV antiretroviral therapy (ART) lowers transmission risk","Treatment reduces perinatal transmission to ~1–2%","Avoid invasive procedures; use universal precautions (gloves for body fluids)","Elective C-section if indicated, before membranes rupture","Bottle-feed where formula is available (breast milk can carry HIV)"]},
    {s:"Cardiac Disorders in Pregnancy",a:"cardiac-disorders-in-pregnancy",k:["Cardiac Disorders in Pregnancy","Pregnancy increases cardiac output, heart rate, and blood volume — a strain when cardiac reserve is already reduced.","Congenital heart disease — Present from birth — e.g., a septal defect or valve dysfunction","Peripartum cardiomyopathy — Left-ventricular dysfunction from the last month of pregnancy up to ~5 months postpartum; edema, cough, chest pain, fatigue","Eisenmenger syndrome — Left-to-right shunting that leads to pulmonary hypertension","Mitral valve prolapse — Mitral valve prolapses into the left atrium during systole; systolic murmur from regurgitation","Signs of cardiac decompensation (assess at each visit; note if progressive): new cough, dyspnea, edema, murmur, palpitations, rales, and weight gain. Management: 8–10 hrs of rest, diet high in iron/protein and low in sodium, epidural to …"]},
    {s:"Early-Pregnancy Bleeding & At-Risk Conditions",a:"early-pregnancy-bleeding-at-risk-conditions",k:["Early-Pregnancy Bleeding & At-Risk Conditions","Threatened — Cervix closed, placenta still attached — Some bleeding; may have cramping/contractions","Imminent (inevitable) — Cervix dilated, placenta separated — Bleeding present","Incomplete — Fetus delivered but placenta/products of conception retained — Ongoing bleeding","Miscarriages generally occur in the first trimester; ~50% of early losses are due to a chromosomal abnormality. Assess bleeding, vital signs, and the need for Rh immune globulin (RhoGAM for Rh-negative moms). May need a D&C (first trimes…","Ectopic pregnancy — Fertilized egg implants outside the uterus (tube, ovary, cervix); sharp one-sided pain, syncope, referred shoulder pain; may or may not bleed. Low progesterone; hCG doesn't double every 2–3 days — Methotrexate IM as o…","Molar pregnancy (hydatidiform mole) — Proliferation of trophoblast cells. Complete mole = empty egg + sperm; partial = egg + two sperm. Grape-like clusters, dark brown bleeding, uterus larger than dates, no fetal heart tones, high hCG, l…","Hyperemesis gravidarum — Excessive vomiting affecting hydration/nutrition (up to 3% of pregnancies); dehydration, ketonuria, weight loss >5% of pre-pregnancy weight; worst in the first trimester — Vitamin B1 (thiamine) to prevent Wernick…"]},
    {s:"Rh Alloimmunization",a:"rh-alloimmunization",k:["Rh Alloimmunization","An Rh- negative mother exposed to Rh- positive fetal blood forms antibodies that break down fetal red blood cells. It usually doesn't harm the first baby but affects future pregnancies.","If untreated: destruction of fetal RBCs → fetal anemia, hydrops fetalis (extensive swelling; heart failure in ~50%, may be lethal), erythroblastosis fetalis , and kernicterus (neurological brain damage from high bilirubin).","Indirect Coombs — Maternal antibody screen at the first prenatal visit and at 20 weeks","RhoGAM at 28 weeks — Give 300 mcg prophylactically if the antibody screen is negative","Other RhoGAM triggers — After spontaneous/induced abortion, ectopic, invasive procedures (CVS, amniocentesis), or maternal trauma — any time fetal blood could mix","Direct Coombs (at birth) — Done on cord blood. If negative , give RhoGAM within 72 hrs. If positive (already sensitized), don't give RhoGAM — monitor the infant for hemolytic disease","Kleihauer-Betke test — Measures how much Rh-positive blood is in maternal circulation to calculate the RhoGAM dose needed","ABO incompatibility — Mom type O, infant A/B/AB (regardless of Rh). Causes hemolysis and hyperbilirubinemia (jaundice); severe anemia is rare"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week2-hypertensive.html",t:"Hypertensive Disorders",secs:[
    {s:"Hypertensive Disorders",a:"",k:["Week 2 · Topic 4"]},
    {s:"Overview",a:"overview",k:["Overview","Hypertension is the most common medical complication in pregnancy, and preeclampsia is the #2 cause of maternal morbidity and mortality worldwide. The earlier hypertension develops, the greater the risk of severe preeclampsia later. Obes…","Correct BP technique: cuff width ~40% of the arm, with 80% of the arm circumference covered; patient at rest ≥5 min, sitting or semi-reclining, arm at heart level."]},
    {s:"Classifications",a:"classifications",k:["Classifications","Gestational hypertension — SBP ≥140 or DBP ≥90 after 20 weeks — No proteinuria. If BP is still elevated 6 weeks after delivery → chronic hypertension","Mild preeclampsia — SBP ≥140 or DBP ≥90 on two occasions ≥4 hrs apart — Proteinuria >300 mg/24 hr, protein/creatinine ratio ≥0.3, or 1+ dipstick. Even without proteinuria: platelets <100,000, cerebral/vision changes, creatinine >1.1, pul…","Severe preeclampsia — SBP ≥160 or DBP ≥110 on two occasions ≥4 hrs apart — Proteinuria; platelets <100,000; pulmonary edema; new cerebral/vision changes; liver enzymes >2× normal; severe persistent epigastric pain","Eclampsia — Preeclampsia + grand mal seizure — Seizure related to blood pressure; can lead to coma. An obstetrical emergency","HELLP syndrome — Associated with severe preeclampsia — H emolysis, E levated L iver enzymes, L ow P latelets — from RBCs fragmenting through damaged vessels and platelets aggregating at injury sites","Chronic hypertension — SBP ≥140 or DBP ≥90 before pregnancy or before 20 weeks — Or hypertension that persists 6 weeks after childbirth","Chronic HTN with superimposed preeclampsia — Sudden rise in previously controlled BP — New proteinuria, increased edema, need for more antihypertensives, or rising serum uric acid"]},
    {s:"Pathophysiology",a:"pathophysiology",k:["Pathophysiology","In preeclampsia, prostacyclin (a vasodilator) is decreased, allowing vasoconstriction and reduced renal perfusion. This decreases placental perfusion → fetal hypoxia. Cell damage activates the coagulation cascade and redistributes intrav…","Prevention: a low dose of 81 mg aspirin started at 12–28 weeks for at-risk patients helps reduce IUGR, preterm birth, and the development of preeclampsia."]},
    {s:"Maternal & Fetal Effects",a:"maternal-fetal-effects",k:["Maternal & Fetal Effects","Maternal effects","Epigastric pain (liver) and elevated liver enzymes from vasoconstriction","CNS: headache, blurred vision, scotoma (blind spots, flashing lights, black dots)","Low platelets, DIC, renal failure, HELLP","Proteinuria, facial & pulmonary edema, ascites, pleural effusions","Oliguria (poorly perfused kidneys)","Fetal effects","Placental abruption","Abnormal umbilical artery Doppler (abnormal placental blood flow)","Oligohydramnios","Intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR)","Stillbirth","Risk factors: chronic hypertension, chronic renal disease, diabetes, Rh incompatibility, first pregnancy, family history of preeclampsia, age <20 or >40, multiple gestation, IVF, and new paternity."]},
    {s:"Assessment & Monitoring",a:"assessment-monitoring",k:["Assessment & Monitoring","Labs: CBC, liver enzymes, chemistry panel, type & screen. A 24-hour urine for protein and creatinine clearance is more accurate than a quick dipstick.","The more irritated the CNS, the more likely a seizure. Rising reflexes (e.g., 1+/2+ → 3+) signal worsening. Check for clonus by dorsiflexing the foot — taps back against your hand are \"beats of clonus\"; document each foot separately. You…"]},
    {s:"Magnesium Sulfate",a:"magnesium-sulfate",k:["Magnesium Sulfate","Given to prevent convulsions/seizures. Used for eclampsia, severe preeclampsia, and HELLP. Typical loading dose 4–6 g over ~20 min, then a maintenance drip (often 2 g/hr IV). Continue for at least 24 hours postpartum. If a convulsion occ…","Expected side effects","Headache","Nausea and vomiting","Feeling hot and flushed","Tired / sleepy","Some muscle weakness","Signs of toxicity","Decreased or absent reflexes","Decreased respiratory rate","Change in level of consciousness / slurred speech","Arm too heavy to lift, trouble concentrating","Therapeutic range is about 4–7. The antidote for magnesium toxicity is IV calcium gluconate ."]},
    {s:"Eclampsia Management",a:"eclampsia-management",k:["Eclampsia Management","Eclampsia is an obstetrical emergency. You don't try to stop the seizure — you prevent recurrence and protect the patient. Priority is the airway : keep her on her side, note the time/body parts/duration, prevent aspiration and injury (p…"]},
    {s:"Antihypertensives",a:"antihypertensives",k:["Antihypertensives","Labetalol (IV) — Good for acute severe hypertension — but avoid in patients with a history of asthma","Hydralazine (IV) — Helpful for severe hypertension — but not for patients with tachycardia","Nifedipine (oral) — Often used in the postpartum period — but not for patients with tachycardia"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week2-nutrition.html",t:"Maternal Nutrition",secs:[
    {s:"Maternal Nutrition",a:"",k:["Week 2 · Topic 2"]},
    {s:"Role of Nutrients",a:"role-of-nutrients",k:["Role of Nutrients","Carbohydrates — Primary source of energy; fiber supports bowel function (ensure adequate dietary fiber)","Proteins — Maternal tissue growth (uterus, breasts), fetal growth, energy metabolism","Fats — Energy; more completely absorbed in pregnancy (fetal fat deposits ~2% mid-pregnancy, ~12% at term)","Calcium & phosphorus — Mineralization of fetal bones and teeth; acid–base buffering","Iodine — Essential part of thyroxine (thyroid hormone); severe deficiency → cretinism. Good food source: iodized table salt.","Sodium — Metabolism and fluid-balance regulation; not normally restricted in pregnancy","Zinc — Protein metabolism; DNA/RNA synthesis; fetal growth and lactation","Magnesium — Cellular metabolism and bone mineralization","Iron — Oxygen-carrying capacity of blood; expansion of maternal blood volume; low iron is the usual cause of anemia in pregnancy. Good food source: red meat."]},
    {s:"Vitamins",a:"vitamins",k:["Vitamins","Vitamin A — Epithelial cell growth, glycogen synthesis, healthy eyes — Sweet potatoes, carrots, eggs — Fat-soluble — stored in the liver","Vitamin D — Absorption/use of calcium & phosphorus for skeletal development — Fortified milk, cereals, yogurt, orange juice — Fat-soluble — stored in the liver","Vitamin E — Antioxidation; maintains cell membrane health — Almonds, sunflower seeds — Fat-soluble — stored in the liver","Vitamin K — Synthesis of prothrombin for blood clotting — Green leafy vegetables — Fat-soluble — stored in the liver","Vitamin C — Development of connective tissue and the vascular system — Oranges, kiwi, broccoli — Water-soluble — excreted in urine","B vitamins — Cell respiration and glucose oxidation for energy metabolism. Inadequate folic acid (a B vitamin) is associated with neural tube defects. — Green leafy vegetables, poultry, chickpeas — Water-soluble — excreted in urine"]},
    {s:"Calorie & Nutrient Needs",a:"calorie-nutrient-needs",k:["Calorie & Nutrient Needs","Extra calories — About +300 kcal/day during the second and third trimesters","Increased needs — Carbohydrates, protein, calcium, zinc, magnesium, iron, vitamin D, vitamin C, and the B vitamins (thiamine, riboflavin, niacin, B6, B12)","No real change needed — Fat intake, vitamin E, vitamin K, iodine, and sodium","Only required supplement — If diet is adequate, iron is the only supplement truly needed — but since most diets fall short, a daily prenatal vitamin is recommended","MEMORIZE: A woman should get at least 400 mcg of folic acid per day during pregnancy or when trying to conceive."]},
    {s:"Weight Distribution, Hydration & Pica",a:"weight-distribution-hydration-pica",k:["Weight Distribution, Hydration & Pica","Weight is distributed across all of these — not just the baby.","Hydration","Fluid drives biochemical reactions, lubrication, transport, and temperature control","Recommend eight to ten 8-oz glasses of fluid a day","At least half should be water","Pica","Craving and persistent eating of non-nutritive substances","Examples: clay, soil, powdered laundry starch, soap, baking powder","Can lead to iron-deficiency anemia — ask about it during nutritional assessment","Obesity risks in pregnancy: spontaneous abortion, gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, labor induction, higher C-section rate, fetal anomalies, and a predisposition for the child to become obese later."]}
  ]},
  {f:"week3-intrapartum1.html",t:"Intrapartum Care I",secs:[
    {s:"Intrapartum Care I",a:"",k:["Week 3 · Topic 1"]},
    {s:"The Five Ps",a:"the-five-ps",k:["The Five Ps","Passage — The birth passageway — the maternal pelvis, the cervix's ability to efface and dilate, and the ability of the vaginal canal and outlet to distend","Passenger — The fetus — its head, attitude, lie, and presentation","Position — The relationship of the fetal presenting part to the maternal pelvis — includes station and engagement","Powers — Primary (involuntary uterine contractions) and secondary (voluntary maternal pushing) forces","Psyche — The patient's psychological state — fear, anxiety, excitement, fatigue, and her support system"]},
    {s:"1. Passage — the Birth Passageway",a:"1-passage-the-birth-passageway",k:["1. Passage — the Birth Passageway","The baby travels through the bony pelvis → lower uterine segment → cervix (must thin and stretch) → pelvic floor muscles (help the fetus rotate) → vagina → introitus (the vaginal opening). The diameters of the pelvic inlet, mid-pelvis, a…","The Four Pelvis Shapes","Gynecoid — ~50% (most common) — The classic female pelvis. Hips wider and broader; ischial spines less prominent, making a wider opening. Most favorable for vaginal birth.","Android — ~23% — Male-type pelvis with a longer sacrum and a more narrow arch. More likely to lead to CPD (cephalopelvic disproportion).","Anthropoid — ~24% — Similar to apes. Increased risk of the baby being in an occiput posterior position.","Platypelloid — ~3% (least common) — A flat pelvis. The baby may take longer to get into the pelvis, and is more likely to be in a transverse lie (side to side).","Effacement & Dilation","Effacement — The gradual thinning/shortening of the cervix — the shortening of the distance between the internal and external cervical os — 0–100%","Dilation — The gradual opening of the cervix — 0–10 cm","Cervical effacement (0–100%) and dilation (1–10 cm)"]},
    {s:"2. Passenger — the Fetus",a:"2-passenger-the-fetus",k:["2. Passenger — the Fetus","The Fetal Head, Sutures & Fontanelles","The fetal head is made of six bones : the frontal bone, two parietal bones, two temporal bones, and one occipital bone. They are connected by four membranous sutures , and the fontanelles are where the sutures intersect. Sutures and font…","Anterior — Diamond — The largest — By about 18 months after birth","Posterior — Triangle — Smaller — Much earlier — about 6–8 weeks after birth","Fetal skull — bones, sutures, and fontanelles","Fetal Attitude","Attitude is the position of the baby's parts in relation to one another . The normal attitude: rounded back, chin flexed to the chest, thighs flexed on the abdomen, legs flexed at the knees, arms crossed. The biparietal diameter (BPD) is…","Normal fetal attitude (flexion)","Fetal Lie","Lie is the relationship of the fetal long axis to the mother's long axis.","Longitudinal (vertical) — Head down = cephalic ; bottom down = breech","Transverse (horizontal) — A shoulder presentation","Fetal lie — longitudinal (cephalic / breech) vs. transverse (shoulder)","Fetal Presentation","Vertex — Cephalic — Head fully flexed — makes the smallest head diameter . This is what you want.","Military — Cephalic — The chin is not flexed, so it's a little harder to fit through","Brow — Cephalic — The brow presents first — very difficult to deliver vaginally","Face — Cephalic — Rare. These babies usually don't want to move down the birth canal; more common in someone who has had a baby before. The face is usually very bruised and edematous.","Frank breech — Breech (3–4% of births) — Hips flexed, knees extended ; the bottom presents first","Complete breech — Breech — Hips and knees flexed, thighs on the abdomen; the bottom and feet present","Footling breech — Breech — Hips and legs extended . Single footling = one foot; double footling = both feet and legs coming through","Shoulder — Transverse lie (~1% of births) — The shoulder is the presenting part","Breech presentations — frank, complete, footling"]},
    {s:"3. Position, Station & Engagement",a:"3-position-station-engagement",k:["3. Position, Station & Engagement","Fetal Station","Station is the relationship of the presenting part to the mother's ischial spines — the smallest, most narrow part of the pelvis. The ischial spines are zero station . Above the spines = a negative number (−1 to −5). Below the spines = a…","Engagement occurs when the presenting part reaches zero station . Before that — when the head is not down in the pelvis — the baby is described as ballotable and floating , i.e. not engaged.","Fetal station relative to the ischial spines (0 station)","Fetal Position — the Three-Letter Notation","Position is the relationship of the presenting part to the mother's pelvis, written with three landmarks. Right and left always refer to the MOTHER's right and left.","1st — side — Which side of the maternal pelvis the presenting part is closest to — R (right) or L (left)","2nd — landmark — What the fetal presenting part is — O = occiput (head) · M = mentum (chin) · S = sacrum (bottom) · A = acromion process (scapula/shoulder)","3rd — direction — Whether that part points toward the mother's front or back — A (anterior) · P (posterior) · T (transverse)","What you want is an ANTERIOR position — the baby's face toward the floor at delivery, not face up. ROA = the occiput is on the mother's right and toward her anterior side. ROP = the occiput is still on her right, but toward her back — so…","Fetal positions — the three-letter notation"]},
    {s:"4. Powers",a:"4-powers",k:["4. Powers","Primary Forces — Uterine Contractions (involuntary)","The primary forces are the uterine muscular contractions , and they are what is responsible for cervical effacement and dilation . They are involuntary.","Increment — The phase as the contraction builds/increases","Acme — The peak of the contraction","Decrement — The phase as the contraction loosens and goes back down","Resting period — The time between contractions — where you check the resting tone","Frequency — The beginning of one contraction to the start of the next — measured in minutes","Duration — The start of a contraction to the end of that same contraction — measured in seconds","Intensity — How strong the contraction is — described as mild, moderate, or strong","Contraction phases — increment, acme, decrement","Secondary Forces — Maternal Pushing (voluntary)","Bearing down & the Ferguson reflex","Secondary forces are the mother voluntarily bearing down , using her abdominal muscles to help push.","The Ferguson reflex is the maternal urge to bear down, caused by the release of endogenous oxytocin when stretch receptors in the vagina are activated as the baby moves down.","Be careful of too much Valsalva maneuver — although commonly used, it reduces blood flow to the mother and the baby.","Why upright positions help","Walking, sitting, kneeling, and squatting all use gravity , which makes contractions stronger.","Upright positions increase cardiac output , and blood flow to the placenta, uterus, and maternal kidneys .","Frequent position changes relieve fatigue, increase comfort, and increase circulation."]},
    {s:"5. Psyche",a:"5-psyche",k:["5. Psyche","What patients feel","Fear and anxiety — of the pain , of loss of control , of themselves or the baby being hurt.","Excitement, joy, and anticipation — they have waited a long time for this baby.","Exhaustion, from the work of labor or just the stress of pregnancy.","Factors linked to a positive birth experience","Trusting her nurse, and being empowered to make her own decisions .","Having attended childbirth classes.","Anything that increases her self-confidence and self-esteem .","Receiving clear information about what you are doing with her.","Determine her level of social support — is there a partner or father of the baby involved? Who is her support system?"]},
    {s:"When the Five Ps Go Wrong",a:"when-the-five-ps-go-wrong",k:["When the Five Ps Go Wrong","Passageway — A pelvis that is too small — makes vaginal delivery difficult","Passenger — A malpresentation or an odd position — e.g. occiput posterior, which is simply harder to push out","Powers — Inadequate contractions , or a patient who is too tired to push effectively","Psyche — Intense fear, anxiety, poor support systems, and exhaustion"]},
    {s:"Signs of Impending Labor",a:"signs-of-impending-labor",k:["Signs of Impending Labor","Lightening — The fetal presenting part settles into the true pelvis. Usually gradual. It relieves pressure on the diaphragm — but as the baby drops lower it puts more pressure on the bladder .","Braxton Hicks — False-labor contractions — the uterus \"practicing\" for the real thing","Cervical changes — Effacement and dilation begin","Bloody show — Expulsion of the mucus plug — brown or blood-tinged cervical mucus. The mucus plug's job is to keep organisms out of the cervix, so losing it (or a burst of bloody mucus) can mean the cervix is starting to soften/open — but…","Rupture of membranes — The water breaks","Nesting — A sudden burst of energy","Weight loss / GI upset — She's just not very hungry, and may have GI upset"]},
    {s:"True Labor vs. False Labor",a:"true-labor-vs-false-labor",k:["True Labor vs. False Labor","The single biggest discriminator: cervical change happens with TRUE labor.","Cervix — Progressive change in dilation and effacement — Generally no change in dilation or effacement","Contraction pattern — Regular ; get closer and closer together — Irregular ; usually no change in intervals or intensity","Pain — They start hurting more over time — Stays about the same","Effect of rest / warm bath / massage — Does NOT make them less painful or less intense — Rest, warmth, and massage ease the pain"]},
    {s:"The Four Stages of Labor",a:"the-four-stages-of-labor",k:["The Four Stages of Labor","First — Onset of true labor — Fully dilated (10 cm). Made up of three phases : latent, active, transition.","Second — Full dilation — Birth of the baby (\"the pushing stage\")","Third — Birth of the baby — Delivery of the placenta","Fourth — Delivery of the placenta — Up to 4 hours postpartum","The Three Phases of the First Stage","Latent (early labor) — 0–3 cm — Usually the longest phase. Nullipara/primigravida: average ~8 hours. Multipara/multigravida: shorter. — Every 10–30 min, ~30 sec long, mild to moderate intensity — Able to cope with the discomfort; relieve…","Active — 4–7 cm — First-time moms: average ~4 hours. Previous births: ~2 hours or so. — Every 2–5 min, 40–60 sec long, moderate to strong on palpation — Anxiety increases; needs energy and focus; fears loss of control; decreased ability …","Transition — 8–10 cm — First-time moms: may last ~3 hours. Multips: may be less than an hour. — Very frequent — every 1½–2 min, 60–90 sec long, very strong to palpation — Withdraws into herself to focus; acutely aware of contraction inte…","Note on cervical history: procedures and scarring on the cervix — e.g. a prior cervical LEEP for an abnormal Pap — can impede effacement and dilation and really extend out the latent phase.","Second Stage — Pushing","Begins with complete cervical dilation and effacement , ends with the birth of the baby . She usually has an urge to push , and crowning occurs as the top of the head starts to come out of the introitus. Contractions are very strong and …","First-time mom — May push up to 3 hours — that's considered normal","Previous births — Usually less than an hour ; the average is about 15–20 minutes","Emotionally she is often relieved that the acute pain is over and that she can finally push, and she has a sense of control because she is actively involved. She may also become frightened knowing it's coming soon, feel overwhelmed by th…"]},
    {s:"The Mechanisms of Labor",a:"the-mechanisms-of-labor",k:["The Mechanisms of Labor","How the baby actually moves and rotates in order to be born, in order:","1. Engagement — The largest part of the fetal presenting part passes through the pelvic inlet","2. Descent — Affected by pressure of the amniotic fluid, contractions, pushing effort, and extension of the fetus","3. Flexion — The head and chin are brought closer to the chest, so the smaller head diameter presents to the pelvic outlet","4. Internal rotation — The fetal head rotates from occiput transverse to occiput anterior","5. Extension — The occiput comes, then the face, then the chin delivers","6. External rotation — The head rotates back to the OT position; the provider delivers the anterior, then the posterior shoulder","7. Expulsion — Birth of the baby","Cardinal movements (mechanisms) of labor"]},
    {s:"Third Stage — Delivery of the Placenta",a:"third-stage-delivery-of-the-placenta",k:["Third Stage — Delivery of the Placenta","The third stage should last no longer than 30 minutes. If it does, there is a risk for hemorrhage and retained placenta .","Signs of placental separation","A globular uterus","The uterus rises in the abdomen","A gush or trickle of blood","More and more of the umbilical cord becomes visible","Management & the two placental sides","Oxytocin is given as an IV bolus right after the placenta delivers , to decrease blood loss.","Do fundal massage to check that the uterus stays firm.","Dirty Duncan = the maternal side, which was attached to the uterus.","Shiny Schultze = the fetal membrane side (chorion and amnion).","IV oxytocin is used not only to induce labor but also to control postpartum bleeding ."]},
    {s:"Fourth Stage — the First 4 Hours After Birth",a:"fourth-stage-the-first-4-hours-after-birth",k:["Fourth Stage — the First 4 Hours After Birth","From delivery of the placenta up to 4 hours postpartum. A great time to promote mother–infant bonding , and a time of physiologic readjustment .","Expected blood loss","Vaginal delivery — Less than 500 mL (average estimated blood loss 250–500 mL)","Cesarean birth — Less than 1,000 mL","Fourth-stage assessment & findings","Fundus, perineum, vaginal bleeding — Every 15 minutes for the first hour","Temperature — At the beginning and end of the recovery period","Post-anesthesia care — Watch for returning sensation; check oxygen saturation","Bladder — Check for fullness . The bladder is often hypotonic — she may need a bedpan or an in-and-out catheter.","Uterus — Should stay contracted and midline in the abdomen, between the symphysis pubis and the umbilicus","Shaking — A CNS response a couple of hours after birth — the body was working hard with a lot of adrenaline pumping, and that strenuous work has now stopped. She also has fluid and heat loss; warm blankets help relax the muscles.","Thirst / hunger — Patients are often very thirsty and hungry","Fundal assessment technique: one hand supports the lower uterine segment , while the other hand rests on top of the abdomen and presses down to feel the top of the fundus. This is done to help control vaginal bleeding and keep the uterus…","Kangaroo care (skin to skin) is encouraged right after birth: it helps regulate the baby's body temperature and heart rate , increases bonding , increases oxytocin release by the mother, and stimulates her breasts — especially good if sh…"]}
  ]},
  {f:"week3-intrapartum2.html",t:"Intrapartum Care II",secs:[
    {s:"Intrapartum Care II",a:"",k:["Week 3 · Topic 2"]},
    {s:"Admission",a:"admission",k:["Admission","Greet the patient and start to establish rapport — a friendly face goes a long way when someone is nervous or hurting. Orient her to the room, facilities, and equipment. Informed consent is important, especially if she is laboring or you…","What the admission assessment must answer","Is she in labor? — And is she term or preterm ?","Is she or the fetus high risk? — Hypertensive disorder, bleeding, diabetes, obesity, a previously large infant, excessive weight gain","Ambulation or bed rest? — Which should be encouraged for this patient","How often to monitor? — Does she need continuous fetal monitoring, or is intermittent enough?","What does she want? — Does she have a birth plan ? Who is her social support?","The birth plan","A birth plan is not \"a kiss of death\" — it's a great idea. It's part of the patient being empowered to help make decisions about her own care. It should cover: the environment she's chosen for labor; her pain management preferences (epid…","Physical assessment & history","Assess & ask","Vital signs; her weight (ask, and weigh her if she doesn't know)","Drug allergies","Medical, surgical, and psychiatric history; social and cultural history","Obstetric history — how many pregnancies, how many deliveries, problems with previous pregnancies or this one","Is the baby moving? Is the baby active?","Current medications; hydration and nutritional status","Admission lab work","Blood type","CBC","Type and screen","Group B Strep (GBS) status — positive or negative","Rubella status — immune, non-immune, or equivocal","Urine dip and/or a urine drug screen","Group B Strep prophylaxis","GBS is an organism that may live in the vaginal flora harmlessly — but it can make the baby ill . Give prophylactic antibiotics during labor, continuing until delivery , so the baby has extra protection if it comes into contact with GBS.…"]},
    {s:"Fetal & Uterine Monitoring Devices",a:"fetal-uterine-monitoring-devices",k:["Fetal & Uterine Monitoring Devices","Placing the external monitors: the toco (contraction monitor) goes on the fundus of the uterus. The ultrasound goes where the fetal shoulders are — that's the loudest spot to hear the baby's heartbeat.","External ultrasound fetal heart rate — Continuous graph of the fetal heart rate — baseline, variability, and changes — Non-invasive; does not require ruptured membranes; nurses can place it — Interference if mom or baby is moving a lot —…","External toco contractions — Contraction frequency and duration — plus a permanent continuous recording of uterine activity — Non-invasive and easy for the nurse to place; can be used before or after rupture of membranes; can be used int…","Fetal scalp electrode (FSE) fetal heart rate · internal — Continuous, clear fetal heart tracing with better information about variability — Keeps tracing even when mom moves, stands, or is on hands and knees — no readjusting. Nurses can …","Intrauterine pressure catheter (IUPC) contractions · internal — Frequency, duration, resting tone — and it calculates INTENSITY for you — Used when the external toco is not sufficient to pick up contractions or uterine activity (often re…","External monitors — ultrasound (FHR) and toco (contractions)","Internal monitors — fetal scalp electrode (FSE) and intrauterine pressure catheter (IUPC)"]},
    {s:"Uterine Activity — the Numbers",a:"uterine-activity-the-numbers",k:["Uterine Activity — the Numbers","Montevideo units (MVUs) measure the intensity of contractions and diagnose whether labor is adequate . How to calculate: subtract the baseline uterine resting pressure from the peak of each contraction in a 10-minute period , then add al…","Montevideo units — Greater than 200 in a 10-minute period — That's what defines adequate labor","MVU ceiling — Do not exceed 300 — Means the uterus has too much pressure / she is contracting too much","Resting tone — Less than 25 mm Hg — The uterus must relax between contractions","Duration — Less than 120 seconds per contraction — A duration greater than 2 minutes is lasting too long","Frequency — No more than 5 contractions in 10 minutes — ideally every 2–3 minutes — Any more and the uterus never gets to rest","Uterine tachysystole — 6 or more contractions in a 10-minute period — This is the definition — too many contractions"]},
    {s:"Rupture of Membranes",a:"rupture-of-membranes",k:["Rupture of Membranes","SROM = spontaneous rupture of membranes. AROM = artificial rupture of membranes.","COAT — what to document when the water breaks: C olor (clear — a faint yellow tint from fetal urine is normal; bloody can signal an abruption; meconium = the infant's stool) · O dor (odorless is normal; a foul smell suggests infection of…","Tests for rupture of membranes","Nitrazine paper — The nurse — non-invasive, right at the bedside — Touch the pH paper to the discharge. Amniotic fluid is alkaline , so it turns the paper a deep blue = POSITIVE . If it stays yellow , it is probably not amniotic fluid.","Fern test — The provider — A sample of vaginal discharge is looked at under the microscope. A crystallized, fern-like formation = a positive fern test = her water is broken.","AmniSure — The provider — Swab and swirl the vaginal discharge ~1 min, transfer to solvent ~1 min, then insert the test strip and read at 5 minutes . Two lines = positive (even a very faint broken second line counts). Control line only =…","Reading an AmniSure (ROM) test"]},
    {s:"Vaginal Exam & Leopold's Maneuvers",a:"vaginal-exam-leopold-s-maneuvers",k:["Vaginal Exam & Leopold's Maneuvers","The bimanual exam (two fingers, sterile glove) checks the cervix and the presenting part. You want to determine: is the baby head-first, breech, or transverse ? Is the cervix posterior, mid-position, or anterior ? Dilation (0–10 cm)? Eff…","Leopold's maneuvers — how the nurse determines position manually","1st — Feel the top of the fundus — head or bottom? — Hard and round = probably the head. Soft or hard to feel = probably the bottom.","2nd — Hands on the sides — arms/legs or back? — Bumpy = arms or legs. Smooth = the baby's back.","3rd — Palpate over the symphysis pubis — the presenting part — Hard = the head. Soft or hard to feel = the bottom.","4th — Feel the outline of the fetus with your palms — The higher the head is in the pelvis, the more of the baby you'll feel.","First maneuver — fundus","Second maneuver — sides (locate the back)","Third maneuver — presenting part","Fourth maneuver — descent","Leopold's also tells you where to put the ultrasound transducer , because you hear the heartbeat best over the fetal shoulders and back . Breech presentation → listen in the right or left upper quadrant. Vertex (head down) → listen in th…"]},
    {s:"Reading the Fetal Heart Tracing",a:"reading-the-fetal-heart-tracing",k:["Reading the Fetal Heart Tracing","🎮 Extra practice — fetal tracing game: Your professor shared an interactive fetal-monitoring game. Practice reading real tracings — accelerations, decelerations, and patterns — at ncc-efm.org .","Episodic — NOT associated with a contraction","Periodic — IS associated with / happens with a contraction","Baseline — Normal fetal heart rate baseline is 110–160 bpm . You must observe the heart rate for at least 10 minutes to determine it.","Accelerations — ≥32 weeks: at least 15 bpm above baseline for at least 15 seconds . <32 weeks: 10 bpm above baseline for 10 seconds. (Same criteria as the non-stress test.)","Variability — the single best indicator","Fetal heart rate variability — how much the heart rate fluctuates around the baseline — is the BEST indicator of fetal oxygenation.","Absent — Undetectable — looks like a straight line — The baby may be acidotic / in distress","Minimal — Less than 5 bpm — May be a fetal sleep cycle , pain medication, or something relaxing (e.g. she's been on magnesium sulfate a while)","Moderate — 6–25 bpm — This is where you want it.","Marked — Greater than 25 bpm — Above the desired range","FHR variability — absent, minimal, moderate, marked","Decelerations — VEAL CHOP","VEAL CHOP: V ariables = C ord compression · E arly = H ead compression · A ccelerations = O kay · L ate = P lacental insufficiency","Early — Head compression — Mirrors the contraction — you could flip it upside down and it would look the same. Slow and gradual: >30 seconds from onset to nadir. The nadir (lowest point) is at the peak of the contraction, and it returns …","Late — Uteroplacental insufficiency — a perfusion problem — The heart rate starts dropping around the peak of the contraction, and has NOT returned to baseline by the time the contraction ends. — Find the perfusion problem: is her BP too…","Variable — Cord compression — Abrupt onset — less than 30 seconds from baseline to nadir — and less than 2 minutes long. Can happen with or without contractions, any time the cord is pinched. — Think: what position change can I do to tak…","Prolonged — Most often umbilical cord prolapse (the cord gets compressed and stays compressed) — ≥2 minutes but less than 10 minutes. (At 10 minutes it would be considered a new baseline.) — It may start out looking like a variable or a …","Decelerations — early (head compression), late (uteroplacental insufficiency), variable (cord compression)","Two patterns you must recognize immediately","Sinusoidal pattern — a perfect, even waveform you could cut in half down the middle. The baby may be acidotic and it is very important that this patient be delivered . Notify your provider immediately.","Fetal bradycardia — Baseline less than 110 bpm for at least 10 minutes — Big culprits: prolapsed cord , or a placental abruption with a lot of bleeding. Find the cause so you can get the heart rate back to a safe range.","Fetal tachycardia — Baseline greater than 160 bpm for at least 10 minutes — CHECK THE MATERNAL TEMPERATURE FIRST. An elevated maternal temp is often reflected in a tachycardic baby. Also rule out infection and consider medications."]},
    {s:"Reassuring vs. Non-Reassuring — and the Three Categories",a:"reassuring-vs-non-reassuring-and-the-three-categories",k:["Reassuring vs. Non-Reassuring — and the Three Categories","Reassuring","A good baseline (110–160).","Good (moderate) variability .","No repetitive decelerations — occasional decels are okay if the baseline and variability are good. A tracing with a few variables plus an acceleration and good variability is still reassuring .","Non-reassuring — the baby is in distress","Persistent and severe variables","Late decelerations of ANY magnitude","Prolonged decelerations","Absent variability","Sinusoidal pattern","Severe bradycardia or prolonged tachycardia","Category I — Normal — Baseline 110–160, moderate variability , no late or variable decelerations. Early decels are okay — it's still a Category I tracing.","Category II — Indeterminate — Minimal or marked variability; no accelerations; prolonged decels, recurrent variables, or recurrent lates with moderate variability","Category III — Abnormal — Sinusoidal pattern, or absent variability along with recurrent lates, recurrent variables, or bradycardia. A Category III baby needs to be delivered.","Reassuring vs. non-reassuring monitor patterns"]},
    {s:"Interventions for a Non-Reassuring Tracing",a:"interventions-for-a-non-reassuring-tracing",k:["Interventions for a Non-Reassuring Tracing","UNCOIL — \"undo what is occurring\": UN = Undo what's happening · C = Change position · O = Oxygen / turn oxytocin off · I = IV fluid bolus · L = Lower the head of the bed","Position change — Her favorite first move — it works very often, it's non-invasive, and you can do it yourself. The left side particularly helps increase blood flow, but right or left both work.","Turn off the oxytocin — If oxytocin is running and you see late decelerations, turn it off . You can always restart it later with a provider order.","IV fluid bolus — A bolus of LR","Oxygen — 10 L via tight non-rebreather face mask","Lower the head of the bed — Helps increase perfusion","Notify the provider & document — Any time you see something non-reassuring","Tocolytic — If she's contracting too much, too frequently, or too long — terbutaline SUB-Q gives a very quick effect to decrease uterine activity — but check the mother's heart rate first and hold it if she is 120 bpm or higher (terbutal…","Prepare for immediate delivery — If you can't fix the problem. If vaginal delivery is near, the provider may use forceps or vacuum ; if not, she needs a cesarean birth ."]},
    {s:"Nursing Care by Stage",a:"nursing-care-by-stage",k:["Nursing Care by Stage","1st stage — Latent — Anticipatory guidance, information, and support. Encourage ambulation. Offer ice chips/fluids per protocol. Vital signs at least every hour. Temperature every 4 hours — but at least every 2 hours (or more often) if h…","1st stage — Active — Palpate contractions every 15–30 min (or continuous monitoring). Vaginal exams for dilation, effacement, station, and position. Encourage her to void every 1–2 hours to keep the bladder empty. Often start an IV (she …","1st stage — Transition — Stay present — especially if she's going natural. Palpate contractions every 15 min (or continuous). Vaginal exams to assess progress so you know when it's time to push and to have the provider present. FHR every…","2nd stage — Pushing — Sterile vaginal exams to confirm the baby is descending well and in good position. FHR every 5–15 min (or continuous). Maternal vital signs every 30 min (more often if high risk). Provide support and information abo…","3rd stage — Newborn care: stimulation and warmth, vital signs and Apgar scores , newborn identification, physical assessment, and skin-to-skin kangaroo care . Maternal care: monitor for delivery of the placenta, document the time , check…","4th stage — BP, pulse, and respirations every 15 min for the first hour ; temperature hourly . Oxytocin 20 units (or per unit protocol) in her IV fluids to contract the uterus and prevent postpartum hemorrhage. Palpate the fundus every 1…","Two fundal findings to know: a boggy or soft fundus is uterine atony → increased risk of bleeding. A fundus deviated to the side usually means a full bladder that needs emptying.","Pushing technique — open vs. closed glottis: closed glottis is holding the breath and bearing down (a Valsalva push); open glottis is bearing down while letting a little air escape. Open-glottis pushing causes less shift in blood flow to…"]},
    {s:"Comfort Measures",a:"comfort-measures",k:["Comfort Measures","First and second stage","Clear fluids and ice chips; ambulation (especially in the latent phase)","Hydrotherapy — a warm tub or shower; some rooms even allow delivery in the tub","Perineal care; helping her relax between contractions; distraction so she can cope","Effleurage — massage with circular stroking movements using the palm of your hand","Firm pressure on the back or sacrum — especially good for back labor","Visualization ; controlled/patterned breathing (it helps if the nurse or support person breathes along with her); position changes","Second stage adds: a cool cloth , rest between contractions, sips of fluid/ice chips, reassurance that she's doing a good job, and help into a pushing position (which may mean holding up her legs)","Positions & gravity","Gravity brings the baby down and relieves pelvic pressure — a birthing ball , a chair at the bedside, or hands and knees all help the baby descend and rotate.","Without an epidural she can kneel, sit, squat, or stand.","The peanut ball is for epidural patients — they can't get out of bed onto a birthing ball. It opens up the pelvis to promote optimal fetal rotation , and is especially good if the baby is occiput posterior , encouraging rotation to occip…","There is no single way to push: stirrups/lithotomy, sitting up in bed, a squat bar , or side-lying."]},
    {s:"Birth & the Immediate Recovery Period",a:"birth-the-immediate-recovery-period",k:["Birth & the Immediate Recovery Period","Signs of imminent birth","The perineum starts bulging or the head is crowning","An uncontrollable urge to bear down","Increased bloody show","As the head comes out, the provider puts pressure and support on the perineal area . Once the head is delivered, suction the mouth and nose , then deliver the shoulders.","After delivery — comfort","Heated blanket / warm covers","Something to eat and drink","An ice pack to her bottom","Pain medication if she needs it","Encourage her to rest — and congratulate her on a job well done","Notify the provider as soon as possible if: she suddenly becomes hypotensive or tachycardic , she has uterine atony , she has excessive bleeding (saturating more than one pad in an hour, or free flow), or she has a hematoma .","Discharge criteria — before transfer to mother-baby / postpartum","Vital signs — Stable","Bleeding — Stable","Bladder — Empty","Fundus — Firm","Anesthesia — If she had it, she should be reporting returning sensation","Baby — Admitted with her to the postpartum unit (or to the nursery if needed) — confirm the right baby with the right family"]}
  ]}
];
